# Report on the Frequency of Defensive Gun Use in the United States

The frequency with which guns are used for self-defense in the United States is a subject of extensive research, debate, and controversy. Estimates vary widely, ranging from tens of thousands to several million defensive gun uses (DGUs) annually. This report synthesizes findings from multiple studies, surveys, and analyses to provide a comprehensive, data-driven overview of how often people use guns for self-defense, highlighting methodological differences, potential biases, and the implications of these findings.

---

## Overview of Defensive Gun Use Estimates

### High-End Estimates

Several large-scale surveys and studies suggest that defensive gun use in the U.S. occurs between **1.67 million and 3 million times per year**. The 2021 National Firearms Survey (NFS), which utilized advanced digital and internet-based methodologies, estimated DGUs at approximately 1.67 to 2.8 million annually. This estimate aligns reasonably well with earlier smaller surveys and private studies conducted over the past few decades ([Weingarten, 2021](https://www.ammoland.com/2021/09/survey-validates-estimates-of-private-guns-and-defensive-uses/)).

Similarly, criminologists Gary Kleck and Marc Gertz, through their 1993 National Self-Defense Survey, estimated over **2.2 million defensive gun uses annually** in the 1990s, a figure that remains influential in the debate ([Capital Research Center, 2018](https://capitalresearch.org/article/why-is-the-cdc-hiding-its-defensive-gun-use-statistics/)).

### Low-End Estimates

Contrasting sharply with the high-end figures, the National Crime Victimization Survey (NCVS), a large government survey designed primarily to measure victimization rather than defensive gun use, estimates DGUs at around **108,000 to 150,000 per year**. This figure is often cited by gun control advocates and some researchers as more reliable due to the NCVS's rigorous methodology and large sample size ([Cook & Ludwig, 1996](https://injuryprevention.bmj.com/content/6/4/263)).

The NCVS's lower estimates have been criticized for methodological limitations, such as excluding defensive uses not associated with reported crimes and underreporting due to the survey design ([Weingarten, 2021](https://www.ammoland.com/2021/09/survey-validates-estimates-of-private-guns-and-defensive-uses/)).

### Mid-Range and Alternative Estimates

Other studies and meta-analyses offer intermediate estimates, typically ranging from **250,000 to 500,000 DGUs annually**. These figures attempt to balance the potential overestimation biases of self-reported surveys and the underestimation biases of victimization surveys ([Hemenway et al., 2015](https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/hicrc/firearms-research/gun-threats-and-self-defense-gun-use-2/)).

---

## Methodological Differences and Their Impact on Estimates

The wide range of estimates primarily stems from differences in survey design, question framing, and data collection methods:

| Aspect                          | High Estimates (1.67M - 3M)                          | Low Estimates (~100K - 150K)                        |
|---------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------|
| **Survey Type**                 | Self-report surveys with broad questions on DGU    | National Crime Victimization Survey (NCVS)         |
| **Sample Size**                 | Large internet-based samples (e.g., 54,000+ people) | Large, nationally representative household surveys |
| **Question Framing**            | Direct questions about any defensive gun use        | Questions limited to reported victimization events |
| **Inclusion Criteria**          | Includes all DGUs, even without reported crimes     | Only includes DGUs tied to reported crimes         |
| **Potential Biases**            | Social desirability bias, false positives            | Underreporting due to narrow scope, telescoping    |
| **Data Collection Method**     | Internet and telephone surveys                        | Repeated household interviews                       |

The **“false positive” problem** in surveys of rare events, as highlighted by Hemenway (1997), explains how even a small percentage of inaccurate responses can dramatically inflate estimates of DGUs ([Harvard Injury Control Research Center, 2017](https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/hicrc/firearms-research/gun-threats-and-self-defense-gun-use-2/)).

Conversely, the NCVS's design, which excludes incidents not reported as crimes and uses bounding techniques to reduce telescoping (misreporting of event timing), likely leads to underestimation of DGUs ([Injury Prevention, 2000](https://injuryprevention.bmj.com/content/6/4/263)).

